{
    "analysis": "From the prior executor output we have a global view of telemetry and top components/KPIs. Many services appear, but the allowed root-cause candidates for this task are restricted to: ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service. We must therefore compute global thresholds (P95) for each KPI of these candidate services using the full available series, then inspect data inside the incident window (2024-01-24 10:51:59 to 2024-01-24 11:21:59 UTC) to find KPI points that breach those thresholds. The previous step did not focus only on these five candidate services, so next we must narrowly analyze metrics (and later traces/logs) for those services only to detect anomalies that could indicate faults.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv (parse timestamp with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True)). Restrict analysis to rows whose cmdb_id is one of the five candidate services: ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) group compute global P95 using the full available series (do NOT filter by incident window for P95 calculation). Then filter the metric rows to the incident window [2024-01-24 10:51:59 UTC, 2024-01-24 11:21:59 UTC] inclusive. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) produce a compact aggregate with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, count_in_window, anomaly_count (count of rows in window with value > global_p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC as ISO string) or NaN if none, max_value_in_window, mean_value_in_window. Return only groups where anomaly_count > 0, order by anomaly_count desc then count_in_window desc, limit to top 20 rows. Also return a separate small list of which of the five candidate services had no metric rows at all (if any)."
}

{
    "analysis": "You have already computed global P95 thresholds for metrics and filtered the incident window. Results show anomalous excursions (value > global P95) in multiple resource and latency KPIs for three services: ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, and ts-route-service. Each flagged KPI has short repeated anomalies (anomaly_count=2) within the incident window; ts-train-service and ts-travel-service had no metric anomalies. To determine the root-cause service among the three faulty services we must use traces next (per rule: if multiple service-level faulty components exist, the root cause is typically the most downstream faulty service in trace call chains). Trace analysis should focus on traces that reference these services (either as source or destination) and look for anomalies in trace duration_p95/duration_mean/error_rate/row_count compared to their global thresholds, restricted to the incident window. This will help identify which of the three is downstream and shows the most significant degradation correlated with metric anomalies.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv (parse timestamp with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True)). Identify trace rows whose trace_name mentions any of the candidate services: ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service (i.e., trace_name contains the substring 'ts-auth-service' or 'ts-order-service' etc.). For each group (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute the global P95 using the full available series (do NOT restrict to the incident window for P95). Then filter the trace rows to the incident window [2024-01-24 10:51:59 UTC, 2024-01-24 11:21:59 UTC] inclusive. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) produce a compact aggregate with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_p95, count_in_window, anomaly_count (value > global_p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC ISO string) or NaN if none, max_value_in_window, mean_value_in_window. Return only groups where anomaly_count > 0, ordered by anomaly_count desc then count_in_window desc, limit to top 20 rows. Also return the total number of trace rows in the window that mention any candidate service and the number of groups with anomalies."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis showed synchronized short bursts of increased traffic (row_count) and elevated latencies (duration_mean/p95) affecting multiple services. Metric analysis earlier found concurrent resource and latency KPI breaches for ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, and ts-route-service (CPU, memory, diskio, socket, latency, workload anomalies). This pattern is consistent with a transient traffic surge that stressed those services. To distinguish the root cause service and the specific failure reason (resource saturation vs. network/socket issues), we need targeted log evidence: whether services logged socket/network errors or resource-related failures, and which service shows the earliest correlated log/traffic anomalies. error_logs.csv was previously empty, so focus on normalized log.csv entries (log.row_count and log.error_count) for the candidate services and inspect actual log-row samples within the incident window for ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, and ts-route-service around the earliest anomaly timestamps (approx 10:54–11:16 UTC).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load log.csv (parse timestamp with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True)). Focus on cmdb_id in [ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service]. For each (cmdb_id, log_name) compute global P95 using the full series (do NOT filter by incident window for P95). Then filter rows to the incident window [2024-01-24 10:51:59 UTC, 2024-01-24 11:21:59 UTC] inclusive. Produce a compact aggregate table with columns: cmdb_id, log_name, global_p95, count_in_window, anomaly_count (value > global_p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC ISO string) or NaN if none, max_value_in_window, mean_value_in_window. Return only groups where anomaly_count > 0, ordered by anomaly_count desc then count_in_window desc, limit to top 20 rows. Also return the top 20 raw log rows (columns: timestamp (ISO UTC), cmdb_id, log_name, value) in the incident window for these three services ordered by value desc (to inspect high row_count or error_count samples). Finally, confirm whether error_logs.csv contains any rows; if yes, return the first 20 rows (timestamp ISO UTC, cmdb_id, message)."
}

